abstract = "This discussion has reviewed some continuing problems of conception and method present in current efforts designed to assess the effectiveness of medical rehabilitation for chronically ill and disabled patients. The clinical adequacy of present efforts is determined by the extent to which: 1.(a)The validity of present definitions of rehabilitation and of assumptions of program benefit for individual patients can be entertained; and2.(b) The degree or extent to which traditional and accepted criteria of program effectiveness are reflective of individual treatment goals. Also illustrated were some gaps between levels of knowledge methodologically required for purposes of controlled studies, and levels of knowledge presently available. The achievement of more clinically adequate research assessments depends upon efforts designed to: 1.(a) Enlarge the base of knowledge of the underlying disease conditions, the processes or components of treatment, and the life course of ill patients; and2.(b) Upon the development of a more relevant conceptual framework of chronic disease patient care, including rehabilitation, embodying appropriate standards and measures of quality of care.",
