abstract = "This article examines a unique sample of elders living with friends and family other than spouses (N = 431). It examines similarities and differences on health, demographic, and caregiving characteristics among elders living with different relations (son, daughter, brother, sister, friend, child plus grandchild, and married child). Three distinctive types of living arrangements are derived from bivariate analyses and subjected to confirmatory factor analyses. Strong support emerges for “dependent elders,” those characterized as living within a married child's household, and by both economic and health disadvantage, as a distinctive type. They are receiving considerable assistance from their married child. Strong support is also evident for “independent elders, ” living in their own household with either sisters or friends, as a distinctive type. While women are more likely to live with sisters and men with friends, both are advantaged, either in terms of socio-economic status or health. Less support was received for the third type, “traditional familial living arrangements,” consisting of those living with all other types of relations. The analyses demonstrate the heterogeneity of those living with someone other than a spouse.",
